```

```{r}
colnames(dta_gaze_raw)
colnames(dta_gaze_aggregated)
```

We have two datasets here. The first (dta_gaze_raw) contains raw fixation point data. The second (dta_gaze_aggregated) contains the mean fixation point data along with additional metadata from the deepfake perceptual experiment. The latter does not have the raw fixation data, so this will need to be added from the former.

# Clustering Fixation Data

In this section, I will apply k-means clustering to the raw fixation data. The goal is to separate fixation points into a few distinct clusters, for example "eyes" and "mouth". This is an improvement upon the initial approach of just looking at the y-axis fixation data as it takes into account both x and y dimensions of the data, and allows for more nuanced categorisation of fixation points.

I will start with k=4.

## k=4

```{r}
# Filter to fixations only
fix_data <- dta_gaze_raw %>% filter(value == "f")

# Per-stimulus k-means
cluster_results <- fix_data %>%
  group_by(stimnopath) %>%
  group_modify(~ {
    coords <- .x %>% select(mean_x, mean_y)
    km <- kmeans(coords, centers = 4, nstart = 25)
    .x %>% mutate(cluster = factor(km$cluster))
  }) %>%
  ungroup()

# Plot a few stimuli to inspect
cluster_results %>%
  filter(stimnopath %in% unique(stimnopath)[1:6]) %>%
  ggplot(aes(mean_x, mean_y, colour = cluster)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.3) +
  scale_y_reverse() +
  facet_wrap(~stimnopath) +
  coord_fixed()
```

From looking at a few select stimuli, we can see that there are clear and distinct clusters for both eyes and mouth regions. However, for some videos, there is a clear "other" cluster, where fixation points reside away from the main facial region. For others, there is a "middle face" cluster, which appears to be related to the nose area.

```{r, fig.width=15, fig.height=15}
cluster_results %>%
  ggplot(aes(mean_x, mean_y, colour = cluster)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.2, size = 0.5) +
  scale_y_reverse() +
  facet_wrap(~stimnopath, ncol = 8) +
  coord_fixed() +
  theme(strip.text = element_text(size = 5))
```

We can see this pattern across the entire dataset too.

Next, I will try k=3 to see if this simplifies the clusters.

## k=3

```{r}
# Filter to fixations only
fix_data <- dta_gaze_raw %>% filter(value == "f")

# Per-stimulus k-means
cluster_results_k3 <- fix_data %>%
