```

This observation holds for the entire dataset.

One thing to check is if this "other" cluster is due to a small number of participants not watching any videos (hence the fixation points outside of the face).

## k=2

Thinking about it, it is probably simpler to just use k=2. This way, we are likely to get a distinct cluster for both eye and mouth regions.

```{r}
# Filter to fixations only
fix_data <- dta_gaze_raw %>% filter(value == "f")

# Per-stimulus k-means
cluster_results_k2 <- fix_data %>%
  group_by(stimnopath) %>%
  group_modify(~ {
    coords <- .x %>% select(mean_x, mean_y)
    km <- kmeans(coords, centers = 2, nstart = 25)
    .x %>% mutate(cluster = factor(km$cluster))
  }) %>%
  ungroup()

# Plot a few stimuli to inspect
cluster_results_k2 %>%
  filter(stimnopath %in% unique(stimnopath)[1:6]) %>%
  ggplot(aes(mean_x, mean_y, colour = cluster)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.3) +
  scale_y_reverse() +
  facet_wrap(~stimnopath) +
  coord_fixed()
```

This confirms my hypothesis. There are clear clusters for upper and lower regions.

```{r, fig.width=15, fig.height=15}
cluster_results_k2 %>%
  ggplot(aes(mean_x, mean_y, colour = cluster)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.2, size = 0.5) +
  scale_y_reverse() +
  facet_wrap(~stimnopath, ncol = 8) +
  coord_fixed() +
  theme(strip.text = element_text(size = 5))
```

And this holds for the entire dataset.

However, this might simplify things too much. There are clearly fixation points outside of the eye and mouth region that would otherwise be picked up by k=3.

We now know from the clustering where the eyes and mouth naturally sit for each stimulus. Next, I will only label fixations that are close the those centroids. Ambiguous fixations will be unassigned or simply "other".

## Label by Centroid Y Position

This part will sort centroids by y coordinate. Lower values (higher on screen) = eyes. Higher values = mouth.

```{r}
cluster_labels <- cluster_results_k2 %>%
  group_by(stimnopath, cluster) %>%
  summarise(cx = mean(mean_x), cy = mean(mean_y), .groups = "drop") %>%
  group_by(stimnopath) %>%
  mutate(region = if_else(cy == min(cy), "eyes", "mouth")) %>%
  select(stimnopath, cluster, region)
```

For each fixation compute distance from assigned cluster centroid:

```{r}
cluster_results_labelled <- cluster_results_k2 %>%
  left_join(cluster_labels, by = c("stimnopath", "cluster")) %>%
  left_join(
    cluster_labels %>% 
      left_join(
        cluster_results_k2 %>%
          group_by(stimnopath, cluster) %>%
          summarise(cx = mean(mean_x), cy = mean(mean_y), .groups = "drop"),
        by = c("stimnopath", "cluster")
      ),
    by = c("stimnopath", "cluster", "region")
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    dist_x = abs(mean_x - cx),
    dist_y = abs(mean_y - cy)
  )
```

Can visualise this:

```{r, fig.width=15, fig.height=15}
cluster_results_labelled %>%
  ggplot(aes(mean_x, mean_y, colour = region)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.2, size = 0.5) +
  scale_y_reverse() +
  facet_wrap(~stimnopath, ncol = 8) +
  coord_fixed() +
  theme(strip.text = element_text(size = 5))
```

The next step is to apply a threshold. This threshold value needs to be data-driven.

## Threshold

One possibility is to compute the standard deviation of x and y distances within each cluster, then set the threshold at some multiple of that (e.g., 1.5 SD).

```{r}
# Compute within-cluster spread per stimulus
cluster_spread <- cluster_results_k2 %>%
  left_join(cluster_labels, by = c("stimnopath", "cluster")) %>%
  group_by(stimnopath, region) %>%
  summarise(
    cx = mean(mean_x),
    cy = mean(mean_y),
    sd_x = sd(mean_x),
    sd_y = sd(mean_y),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

# Then look at the distribution of sd_x and sd_y across all stimuli
cluster_spread %>%
  pivot_longer(c(sd_x, sd_y), names_to = "axis", values_to = "sd") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = sd, fill = region)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30, alpha = 0.7) +
  facet_wrap(~axis) +
  labs(title = "Within-cluster spread by region and axis")
```

Compute thresholds (1.5 SD)

```{r}
threshold_vals <- cluster_spread %>%
  group_by(region) %>%
  summarise(
    threshold_x = 1.5 * median(sd_x, na.rm = TRUE),
    threshold_y = 1.5 * median(sd_y, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

threshold_vals
```

Join centroids & thresholds back to fixation data:

```{r}
cluster_results_labelled <- cluster_results_k2 %>%
  left_join(cluster_labels, by = c("stimnopath", "cluster")) %>%
  left_join(
    cluster_spread %>% select(stimnopath, region, cx, cy),
    by = c("stimnopath", "region")
  ) %>%
  left_join(threshold_vals, by = "region") %>%
  mutate(
    dist_x = abs(mean_x - cx),
    dist_y = abs(mean_y - cy),
    region_final = if_else(
      dist_x <= threshold_x & dist_y <= threshold_y,
      region,
      "other"
    )
  )

# Check how many fixations are retained vs reclassified
cluster_results_labelled %>%
  count(region_final) %>%
  mutate(prop = n / sum(n))
```

Visualise:

```{r}
cluster_results_labelled %>%
  filter(stimnopath %in% unique(stimnopath)[1:6]) %>%
  ggplot(aes(mean_x, mean_y, colour = region_final)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.4) +
  scale_y_reverse() +
  facet_wrap(~stimnopath) +
  coord_fixed() +
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("eyes" = "#F8766D", 
                                  "mouth" = "#00BFC4", 
                                  "other" = "grey70")) +
  labs(title = "Fixations labelled by region after threshold",
       colour = "Region")
```

